Ask HN: Do you skip social proof sections in landing pages?
text:
I've always wondered if I am the only one who never reads the "social proof" section of landing pages.

Who cares about a carefully selected and biased review of a person I don't even know?

Many startups even put this type of section right after the hero section. I feel like that's wasted space.

Ask HN: Has anyone found a good “smart” alarm?
text:
Can anyone recommend a wearable (or frankly anything) that offers a reliable "smart" alarm function?

Background:

I previously owned (and loved) the Microsoft Band 2, and aside from it's terrible durability, I found it to be an excellent fitness/health wearable.

One of the features that I loved the most was the smart alarm. The gimmick here was that you'd set the latest time you'd like to wake, and the band would decide the optimum time to trigger the alarm within a time window leading up to the time you'd set.

It would use input from the various sensors to detect when you were in a light sleep phase and avoid yanking you out of a deeper sleep.

In my experience it worked incredibly well, and I haven't really been able to find an alternative (I've owned a few Fitbit devices since - they just don't come close IMO).

Anyone know of anything that does this job well?

Poll: Should any government be trusted as an Open Identity provider?
text:
For context, in the United States, should the Social Security Administration be an Open Identity provider? Should state Departments of Motor Vehicles be Open Identity providers?

On the one hand, I can see a number of efficiency gains for being able to log into government websites using a single identity or in place of a physical ID.

But on the other, I can see liberty losses if government id is asked for when not legally required or allowed.
